# Contributing to Open-Source Practice

Thank you for your interest in contributing to the Open-Source Practice project! Your contributions help make this project better. This guide provides instructions on how to contribute code, documentation, tests, and more.

## How to Contribute

### 1. Fork the Repository
Visit the repository: [https://github.com/kurosakiichig/open-source-practice.git](https://github.com/kurosakiichig/open-source-practice.git)  
Click the **Fork** button at the top-right corner of the GitHub page to create a copy under your own account.

### 2. Clone Your Fork
Clone your forked repository to your local machine by running:

git clone https://github.com/your-username/open-source-practice.git

Replace with your GitHub username. Then, navigate into the repository directory:your-username

cd open-source-practice

Create a New Branch
Before starting your work, create a new branch for your changes. This helps keep your work organized:
git checkout -b feature/your-feature-name

Replace with a descriptive name for your feature or bug fix (e.g., or ).your-feature-namefeature/add-new-modulefix/issue-42

4. Make Your Changes
Modify the code, update documentation, or add new tests as needed.
Ensure your changes adhere to the project's coding style and guidelines.
5. Commit Your Changes
Stage your changes and commit them with a clear, descriptive message:
git add .
git commit -m "feat: add new feature [describe your change]"

6. Push Your Branch and Create a Pull Request
Push your branch to your fork on GitHub:
git push origin feature/your-feature-name

Then, navigate to your repository on GitHub and click the Compare & pull request button to create a new pull request (PR). In the PR description, detail your changes and the reasoning behind them.

Code and Documentation Guidelines
Code Style: Please follow the existing coding style in the project. If a style guide is provided, adhere to it.
Comments and Documentation: Include meaningful comments and update documentation as necessary, especially for complex logic.
Testing: Ensure that your changes pass existing tests and add new tests if applicable.
Reporting Issues
If you encounter any problems or have suggestions for improvements, please check the Issues page first. If your issue hasn't been reported, feel free to open a new issue with a clear description.

Thank You!
Thank you again for your interest in contributing to the Open-Source Practice project. Every contribution, no matter how small, helps make this project better!

